// Regression test for a known compiler crash: calling a generic class's
// method directly as an if-condition (or any inline expression context
// that isn't first assigned to a local variable) crashes FIR->FLIR
// lowering.
//
// Reproduction: if (some_opt.isSome()) { ... } fails with
//   LoweringError: unsupported FIR operand NoneType
// raised from val() in firescript/flir/lowering.py, reached via
// lower_terminator() when resolving the branch condition operand.
// The same crash also reproduces for println(some_opt.isSome()) (an
// inline call as a function argument, not just as a branch condition) --
// see lower_call() -> val() in the traceback. Assigning the call result
// to an intermediate bool variable first (as in
// option_issome_isnone_regression.fire) avoids this particular crash and
// isolates the separate isSome()/isNone() wrong-value bug.
//
// Expected (correct) behavior once fixed: prints "some".
import @firescript/std.io.println;
import @firescript/std.types.Option;

Option<int32> some_opt = Option<int32>(42);
if (some_opt.isSome()) {
    println("some");
} else {
    println("none");
}
